{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619301"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:30:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:30:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0,0.4,0.54,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75175"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9238"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60683"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"3234"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"6272"},{"type":"tags","id":"6612"},{"type":"tags","id":"7142"},{"type":"tags","id":"9386"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21890"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21893"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75175"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EParkinson\u0027s disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder characterised by motor symptoms including tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following brain regions shows the primary loss of dopaminergic neurons in Parkinson\u0027s disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dorsal striatum","Globus pallidus interna","Substantia nigra pars reticulata","Substantia nigra pars compacta","Globus pallidus externa"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hallmark pathology of Parkinson\u0027s disease is the progressive loss of dopaminergic neurons in the \u003Cstrong\u003Esubstantia nigra pars compacta\u003C/strong\u003E. These neurons normally project to the \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal striatum\u003C/strong\u003E via the nigrostriatal pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other regions mentioned have different roles in the basal ganglia circuitry:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobus pallidus interna\u003C/strong\u003E is an output nucleus of the basal ganglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstantia nigra pars reticulata\u003C/strong\u003E is also an output nucleus and contains GABAergic neurons\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobus pallidus externa\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the indirect pathway of the basal ganglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe loss of dopaminergic input to the striatum leads to the characteristic motor symptoms of Parkinson\u0027s disease through disruption of basal ganglia circuitry.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parkinson\u0027s disease is characterised by progressive loss of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra pars compacta.","Loss of these neurons leads to reduced dopamine signaling in the basal ganglia, resulting in classic parkinsonian motor symptoms.","The substantia nigra pars compacta projects primarily to the dorsal striatum via the nigrostriatal pathway."],"references":["Alexander GE. Biology of Parkinson\u0027s disease: pathogenesis and pathophysiology of a multisystem neurodegenerative disorder. Dialogues Clin Neurosci. 2004 Sep;6(3):259-80. doi: 10.31887/DCNS.2004.6.3/galexander. PMID: 22033559; PMCID: PMC3181806.","Dickson DW. Parkinson\u0027s disease and parkinsonism: neuropathology. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2012 Aug 1;2(8):a009258. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a009258. PMID: 22908195; PMCID: PMC3405828.","Parent M, Parent A. Substantia nigra and Parkinson\u0027s disease: a brief history of their long and intimate relationship. Can J Neurol Sci. 2010 May;37(3):313-9. doi: 10.1017/s0317167100010209. PMID: 20481265.","Sonne J, Reddy V, Beato MR. Neuroanatomy, Substantia Nigra. 2024 Sep 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725680.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60683"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T09:14:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:03:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9238"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75175"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+1